i've got another idea for a potential story where : a 21 yo guy , same age as me -- who struggles with internal turmoil , various thoughts as if it were a voice that wouldn't hesitate to do several things that he would do , he generally just backs off from various things that could seem bothering to him , to raise his voice and not get into any trouble --- more like , he thinks about making it big in the world , proving that he mattered and him being known in the world atleast , but inside him his thoughts would want the same , but more pyschotic , more rageful , no hesitation , like a don't care attitude though ... eventually something happens in his area or city where his thoughts develop a personality within and can switch places within his body under certain conditions ... so its like 2 people in the same body .. what do you think of it ?... in a nutshell : a guy suffering from his other counter self born from a certain incident that happened in his city , both having a same goal -- to make it big in life and prove their matter of existence
I think this is a really compelling concept with a lot of dramatic potential! You're tapping into some fascinating psychological territory here. Let me break down what's working:
Strong Core Conflict: The setup of two personalities sharing the same body but with different approaches to the same goal creates inherent tension. One wants to "make it big" through restraint and playing it safe, while the other wants to bulldoze through without hesitation. That's gold for character-driven storytelling.
Relatable Starting Point: A 21-year-old feeling stuck, holding back, wanting to prove himself but being paralyzed by overthinking—that's incredibly relatable. Many people at that age (including yourself) can connect with that feeling of having ambition but being their own worst enemy.
The Twist: The idea that an external incident in the city manifests this internal struggle as a literal split personality is intriguing. It raises questions: Was this voice always dormant? Did the incident unlock something in multiple people? Is he the only one affected?
Some things to consider as you develop it:
•	The Switching Mechanism: You mentioned "certain conditions"—what triggers the switch? Stress? Anger? Time of day? Loss of control? This could be a great source of tension if he's trying to prevent the switch at crucial moments.
•	Shared Memories: Do they both remember what the other does? Or does he wake up to consequences he doesn't remember causing? The latter could be terrifying.
•	The End Goal: They both want to "make it big"—but what does that actually mean to each of them? The cautious one might want recognition through legitimate success, while the reckless one might not care how he gets known.
•	The City Incident: This is your wildcard. What happened? Was it supernatural, a chemical spill, a collective trauma? This could tie into the larger world-building.
Overall: This has shades of Fight Club, Moon Knight, and classic Jekyll/Hyde stories, but with your own spin. The key will be making both personalities fully realized characters rather than just "good guy/bad guy."
What's your vision for the tone? Psychological thriller? Dark comedy? Action-driven?
