PN
switching mechanism could more like a pact between them but the main soul governs the body and only loses it when he loses to make a point at all , and pls do come up with smtg better if this is not cool enough... , i wanna keep it dark comedy , psychological thriller , action driven like jjk or chainsaw man
Okay, now we're talking! That JJK/Chainsaw Man vibe totally reframes this. Let me build on your pact idea and elevate it:
The Pact/Switching Mechanism:
Your idea of the main soul governing but losing control when he "can't make a point" is solid, but let me refine it:
"The Failure Clause":
•	The main guy (let's call him the "Host") stays in control as long as he's actively trying to achieve their shared goal
•	BUT the moment he hesitates, backs down, or fails to act when opportunity presents itself—snap—the Other takes over
•	It's not just losing an argument—it's losing conviction. The second he doubts himself or retreats into his safe, passive patterns, the switch happens
Why this works for dark comedy + action:
•	Creates panic-inducing moments where he's desperately trying to commit to decisions he's not ready for, just to stay in control
•	The Other can mock him during the switch: "Thanks for the body, coward"
•	Leads to darkly funny situations where he has to do increasingly unhinged things to prove he's "still trying"
Alternative/Addition - "The Bet System": Since you want that Chainsaw Man energy, what if they have an ongoing scoreboard?
•	Every time Host achieves something toward their goal = he stays in control longer
•	Every time he fails/gives up = the Other gets hours/days in the driver's seat
•	They can negotiate control: "Give me the body for this fight, and I'll get us what we need"
•	Creates twisted partnership dynamics like Sukuna/Yuji but with more bickering
The Other's Personality (to fit the vibe):
Don't make him just "evil version"—make him fun:
•	Charismatic, reckless, brutally honest
•	Says everything Host wishes he could say
•	Genuinely doesn't fear consequences because "we're already fucked, might as well enjoy it"
•	Leaves Host with results but also complete social/legal chaos to clean up
•	Think Denji's impulsiveness meets Gojo's arrogance meets Sukuna's bloodlust
The Dark Comedy Sweet Spot:
•	Host wakes up to find the Other got them a promotion... by threatening their boss
•	The Other actually makes friends easier because he's confident, but they're all dangerous people
•	Host tries to apologize to someone; starts losing conviction; feels the switch coming; has to commit to the insult instead
•	The Other leaves notes: "You're welcome for the girlfriend. Don't fuck this up."
What do you think? Does this hit the tone you're going for? Want me to punch up any specific aspect?
