let that be done later but for now -- can the other talk to mc always or just during combat time ?
GREAT QUESTION! This is actually a crucial character dynamic detail. Let me give you options:
________________________________________
OPTION 1: ALWAYS TALKING (Constant Presence)
How it works:
•	The Other can talk to MC anytime, anywhere
•	It's like having a voice in your head 24/7
•	Only MC can hear him (internal dialogue)
Pros for storytelling:
•	Comedy gold: The Other commenting on everything 
o	MC on a date: "Just kiss her already, coward."
o	MC in a meeting: "This guy's lying. Let me handle this."
o	MC trying to sleep: "We should be training right now."
•	Constant tension: MC can never escape himself
•	Character development: They're forced to communicate and understand each other
•	Internal conflict is VISIBLE: Readers/viewers always see both perspectives
Cons:
•	Could get annoying if overused
•	MC might seem "crazy" talking to himself
•	Less impactful when Other actually takes over
Best for: Dark comedy tone, character-driven story, psychological thriller elements
________________________________________
OPTION 2: LIMITED COMMUNICATION (Conditional)
How it works:
•	The Other can only talk during specific conditions: 
o	When Resolve is actively being used
o	During combat/high-stress situations
o	When MC's emotions are intense (anger, fear, desperation)
o	When MC's Resolve drops below a certain threshold (like 30%)
Pros for storytelling:
•	More impactful: When Other speaks, it MEANS something
•	Natural escalation: As story progresses, they communicate more freely
•	Clear danger indicator: Other's voice = shit's getting real
•	MC seems more "normal" to other people
Cons:
•	Harder to develop their relationship outside combat
•	Miss out on comedy moments
•	Less internal dialogue depth
Best for: Action-focused story, clearer distinction between "normal life" and "Resolve life"
________________________________________
OPTION 3: EVOLVING COMMUNICATION (My Recommendation)
How it works - Changes throughout the story:
Phase 1: Post-Collision (Weeks 1-2)
•	Other can barely communicate
•	Just feelings, impulses, anger
•	MC doesn't understand what's happening
•	"Why do I feel like someone's screaming inside me?"
Phase 2: Early Discovery (Weeks 3-4)
•	Other starts forming words
•	Short phrases, usually aggressive
•	Only during high emotion/combat
•	"MOVE!" "FIGHT!" "LET ME OUT!"
Phase 3: The Pact (Month 2 - Current)
•	Full communication unlocked
•	Other can talk anytime, BUT: 
o	MC can "tune him out" if he focuses
o	Other can't force MC to listen outside combat
o	During combat, Other's voice gets LOUD, impossible to ignore
•	Most of the time they argue like roommates
Phase 4: Partnership (Months 3-5)
•	Communication becomes natural
•	MC stops trying to tune him out
•	They start finishing each other's sentences
•	Other's voice becomes less "external" and more like intrusive thoughts
•	"Wait, was that me or you?" - "Does it matter?"
Phase 5: Unification (Late game)
•	The voices blend
•	Sometimes MC doesn't know who's talking
•	Eventually: Single unified internal voice
________________________________________
MY SPECIFIC RECOMMENDATION FOR YOUR STORY:
Start with OPTION 3 - Phase 3 (since you're beginning 2 months post-Collision):
Daily Life:
•	Other CAN talk, but it's like having an annoying roommate
•	MC can have full conversations with him internally
•	MC has learned to "ignore" him when necessary (like during classes, meetings)
•	Other gets bored and fucks with MC for entertainment 
o	"You're really going to eat that? We have a body to maintain."
o	"She's into you. Say something."
o	"This instructor is full of shit. I could teach this better."
Combat/High Stress:
•	Other's voice becomes impossible to ignore
•	Louder, more insistent
•	Can "see" through MC's eyes and comment in real-time
•	"Left! BLOCK LEFT!"
•	"You're dropping your guard!"
•	"Just let me take over already!"
When Resolve is Active:
•	Communication is crystal clear
•	They can share sensory information
•	Other can feel what MC feels and vice versa
•	This is when strategy happens: 
o	"I'll analyze the pattern, you execute when I say."
o	"Three seconds. That's your window."
The Switch:
•	When Other takes over, MC becomes the "voice"
•	Role reversal: Now MC is the one commenting, and Other is in control
•	MC: "Don't kill him!"
•	Other: "Relax, I'm just breaking his legs."
•	MC can't force a switch back, just plead/argue
________________________________________
SPECIFIC SCENE EXAMPLES:
COMEDY (Daily Life):
MC sitting in Resolver training lecture.

Instructor: "—and that's why Core protection is essential—"

Other: *"We already know this. Ask about Resonance."*

MC: (internally) Shut up, I'm trying to pay attention.

Other: *"You're trying to look like a good student. There's a difference."*

MC: (internally) I hate you.

Other: *"No you don't. You need me."*
________________________________________
TENSION (Pre-Combat):
MC on a mission, approaching hostile Ruptured.

Other: *"I can smell his Resolve from here. He's strong."*

MC: (internally) I can handle this.

Other: *"You're going to hesitate. You always do."*

MC: (internally) I won't. Not this time.

Other: *"Then prove it. Or let me do it for you."*

MC feels his Resolve starting to slip.

Other: *"Three... two..."*

MC: (internally) I've got this!

MC charges forward.
________________________________________
COOPERATION (Mid-Fight):
MC fighting, struggling against a faster opponent.

Other: *"He's favoring his right side. Old injury."*

MC: (internally) How do you—

Other: *"I can feel it in his Resolve. It's weaker there."*

MC: (internally) If I feint left—

Other: *"—I can hit right when you switch. Do it."*

They move in sync. Perfect counter.

Other: *"See? We're better together."*

MC: (internally) ...Don't let it go to your head.
________________________________________
CHARACTER DEVELOPMENT (Quiet Moment):
MC alone at night, can't sleep.

MC: (internally) You awake?

Other: *"Always. You know that."*

MC: (internally) ...Do you think we'll ever be normal again?

Other: *"We were never normal. That's the point."*

MC: (internally) That's not reassuring.

Other: *"I'm not here to reassure you. I'm here to make sure we survive."*

Silence.

Other: *"...But we'll figure it out. We always do."*
________________________________________
SO, MY FINAL ANSWER:
The Other can talk to MC always, BUT:
1.	MC can partially tune him out during daily life (requires focus)
2.	Other becomes impossible to ignore during combat/stress
3.	Communication gets clearer as their relationship evolves
4.	Roles reverse when Other takes control (MC becomes the voice)
This gives you: ✓ Comedy potential (always talking) ✓ Tension (can't escape himself) ✓ Clear escalation (communication improves over time) ✓ Action clarity (strategic coordination) ✓ Character depth (forced to understand each other)
Does this work for your vision? Want me to adjust the communication rules, or show more example scenes of how their dynamic would play out?
