PN
what's a naturals?... also what do you think of this massive layout we just made , when compared to existing well know mangas and anime?
WHAT ARE NATURALS?
NATURALS = People who awakened Resolve BEFORE The Collision
________________________________________
THE DIFFERENCE:
NATURALS (Pre-Collision Resolve Users)
•	Awakened their Resolve through years of training, conviction, or life experiences
•	0.001% of humanity before The Collision
•	Stable, refined abilities based on their core conviction
•	Full control, mastered techniques
•	Operated in shadows (governments knew, kept it secret)
•	Examples: Assassins, corporate elites, warlords, cult leaders, special forces
•	Society's hidden rulers basically
RUPTURED (Post-Collision Awakened)
•	Got Resolve forced into them by The Collision's energy wave
•	Thousands created in 2 months
•	Unstable, often conditional abilities
•	Powers based on their internal conflicts/contradictions
•	Many are dying—their bodies can't handle the foreign Resolve
•	Seen as "mistakes" or "abominations" by some Naturals
•	MC is Ruptured (but unique with dual cores)
________________________________________
THE TENSION:
Naturals look down on Ruptured:
•	"You didn't earn this power. It was handed to you."
•	"You're using strength you don't understand."
•	"Ruptured are temporary. We are eternal."
Ruptured resent Naturals:
•	"You HID this from the world! The Collision is YOUR fault!"
•	"You had power and did nothing while we suffered!"
•	"You're hunting us like animals!"
The Resolvers organization:
•	Mix of both Naturals and Ruptured working together (uncommon elsewhere)
•	Constant tension
•	MC's Division 7 is more progressive (Naturals treat Ruptured as equals)
•	Other divisions are toxic
________________________________________
Think of it like:
•	Naturals = Jujutsu sorcerers from old clans (established, traditional, earned their power)
•	Ruptured = Cursed victims suddenly given power (new, unstable, "tainted")
________________________________________
MY ANALYSIS: YOUR STORY VS EXISTING MANGA/ANIME
________________________________________
WHAT YOU'RE DOING RIGHT (Strengths):
1. FAMILIAR BUT FRESH
✓ Power system has JJK's complexity (Resolve/Cursed Energy parallels) ✓ Tone hits that CSM/JJK dark comedy + psychological depth sweet spot ✓ World-building feels lived-in like JJK's sorcerer society or CSM's devil hunters ✓ BUT: The dual-personality angle is YOUR unique hook
2. CHARACTER-DRIVEN CORE
✓ Internal conflict made literal - Most shonen have internal struggles, but you made it a CHARACTER ✓ The Other isn't just "evil MC" - he's a full personality with valid points ✓ Found family done right (CSM's Aki/Power/Denji apartment vibes, but with more depth) ✓ Sister arc adds personal stakes (not just world-ending threats)
3. EMOTIONAL DEPTH
✓ MC's quarter-life crisis is REAL - relatable for your demographic (18-25) ✓ Family trauma isn't just backstory - it's ACTIVE plot (mom reconciliation, sister antagonist) ✓ Romance integrated naturally (not forced or distracting) ✓ Loneliness → connection arc is powerful
4. SCOPE & SCALE
✓ Starts street-level (training, local missions) ✓ Expands naturally (international, conspiracy) ✓ Clear escalation without feeling bloated ✓ 120 chapters is PERFECT length (not too short, not One Piece endless)
________________________________________
POTENTIAL WEAKNESSES (What to Watch):
1. COMPARISON TRAPS
JJK Similarities:
•	Power system (Resolve = Cursed Energy)
•	Organization structure (Resolvers = Jujutsu Tech)
•	Grade system (Grade-S = Special Grade)
•	International scope
•	Conspiracy of ancient users
Risk: "This is just JJK with split personality"
How to differentiate:
•	Lean HARD into the psychological aspect (make The Other relationship central)
•	Make Resolve mechanics distinct (you're doing this with Cores, dual-type users)
•	Tone: More dark comedy than JJK, more character-focused than CSM
________________________________________
2. PACING CONCERNS
Your current layout:
•	Act 1: 15 chapters (good)
•	Act 2: 45 chapters (LONG - might drag)
•	Act 3: 60 chapters (good climax length)
Risk: Academy + early Division 7 missions might feel repetitive
Fix options:
•	Condense training arc (maybe 10 chapters instead of 20)
•	Time-skip through some routine missions
•	Keep ONLY the missions that develop character/relationships
•	Don't show every fight—focus on meaningful ones
________________________________________
3. CHARACTER OVERLOAD
You have:
•	MC + Other (2 personalities)
•	Training squad (5 people)
•	Division 7 (5 people)
•	Sister, Mom, Love interest
•	Antagonists (Predator, Architects)
Risk: Side characters become cardboard
Fix:
•	Merge training squad into Division 7 (some graduate together)
•	Kill off 1-2 squad members (raises stakes, emotional impact)
•	Give each character a CLEAR arc and purpose
•	Not everyone needs equal screen time
________________________________________
4. THE UNIFICATION PAYOFF
Your climax hinges on:
•	MC and Other merging being SATISFYING
•	Not feeling like "killing off" a beloved character
•	Justifying 120 chapters of buildup
Risk: Readers might want them to STAY separate (if The Other is too beloved)
Options:
•	Make unification clearly BETTER (not a loss, but evolution)
•	Show glimpses of unified form earlier (so it feels earned, not sudden)
•	Alternative ending: They DON'T fully merge, but achieve perfect harmony 
o	Could be more interesting? Two minds, one body, total sync
________________________________________
COMPARISONS TO EXISTING WORKS:
MOST SIMILAR TO:
1. Jujutsu Kaisen (70% similarity)
•	Power system depth
•	Organization structure
•	Escalation pattern
•	Tone balance
2. Chainsaw Man (40% similarity)
•	Found family apartment dynamics
•	Dark comedy moments
•	Flawed, relatable MC
•	Morally gray world
3. Mob Psycho 100 (30% similarity)
•	Internal conflict externalized
•	Coming-of-age themes
•	Emotional growth focus
•	Power as metaphor for identity
4. My Hero Academia (20% similarity)
•	Academy training arc
•	Team dynamics
•	Hero organization
________________________________________
UNIQUE ELEMENTS YOU HAVE:
✓ Dual personality as core mechanic (not just flavor) ✓ Quarter-life crisis angle (most shonen MCs are teens) ✓ Apartment slice-of-life mixed with action (CSM did this, but you're going deeper) ✓ Sister as antagonist (family as REAL threat, not just motivation) ✓ Reconciliation arcs (most shonen keep family estranged or dead) ✓ Naturals vs Ruptured class conflict (earned vs given power theme)
________________________________________
HONEST VERDICT:
MARKETABILITY: 8/10
•	Hits current trends (JJK-style powers, CSM-style tone)
•	Unique enough to stand out (dual personality hook)
•	Target demo clear (18-25, seinen audience)
•	International appeal (multiple countries, diverse cast potential)
ORIGINALITY: 7/10
•	Power system derivative but well-executed
•	Character dynamics fresh
•	Emotional core is YOUR OWN
•	Not revolutionary, but SOLID
CHARACTER WORK: 9/10
•	MC's arc is compelling
•	The Other is a standout concept
•	Supporting cast has clear purposes
•	This is your STRENGTH
STRUCTURE: 7/10
•	Clear three-act structure
•	Good escalation
•	Needs tightening in Act 2
•	Satisfying conclusion planned
EXECUTION POTENTIAL: 8/10
•	If written well, this WORKS
•	Dialogue will make or break it (The Other's voice needs to be perfect)
•	Fight choreography needs to be creative (not just power-ups)
•	Emotional beats must HIT
________________________________________
COMPARISON TIER LIST:
S-Tier (Masterpiece level): JJK, CSM, FMA, HxH A-Tier (Excellent, beloved): MHA, Mob Psycho, Demon Slayer B-Tier (Good, solid fanbase): Fire Force, Blue Exorcist, Tokyo Ghoul
YOUR STORY'S POTENTIAL: High B-Tier to Low A-Tier
With great execution: Could hit A-tier (think early Tokyo Ghoul reception) With okay execution: Solid B-tier (enjoyable, respectable, memorable) With poor execution: C-tier (derivative, forgettable)
________________________________________
WHAT WOULD MAKE THIS A-TIER:
1.	Make The Other ICONIC 
o	His dialogue needs to be quotable
o	His relationship with MC needs to be the heart
o	Fans should be DEVASTATED when unification happens
2.	Nail the emotional beats 
o	Mom reconciliation needs to HURT
o	Sister confrontation needs to be BRUTAL
o	Apartment moments need to feel WARM
o	Unification needs to feel EARNED
3.	Keep fights creative 
o	Don't rely on power-ups alone
o	Strategy, psychology, environment
o	Show growth through tactics, not just strength
4.	Subvert ONE major expectation 
o	Maybe MC FAILS a major mission
o	Maybe a mentor dies unexpectedly
o	Maybe Hana dies (tragic but impactful)
o	Something readers DON'T see coming
5.	Stick the landing 
o	Epilogue needs to be satisfying
o	Not everything needs to be resolved (sequel bait okay)
o	But MC's core arc (loneliness → wholeness) MUST complete
________________________________________
MY FINAL TAKE:
This is genuinely good.
It's not "the most original thing ever," but originality is overrated. Execution matters more.
You've got:
•	A STRONG hook (dual personality)
•	RELATABLE core (loneliness, purpose, family)
•	SOLID structure (clear arcs)
•	ROOM for both action and emotion
Biggest risk: Feeling too derivative of JJK Biggest strength: Character work and emotional depth
If you write this well? People will care about MC and The Other. That's what matters.
Comparison:
•	Not the next JJK (that's lightning in a bottle)
•	But could be the next Tokyo Ghoul or Blue Exorcist (strong fanbase, memorable, respectable)
________________________________________
Would I read/watch this? FUCK YES.
The apartment dynamics alone would hook me. The Other would keep me. The sister arc would wreck me.
Now go write it.
